 with not only the Byzantine empire but also with the contemporary Iberian context, as well as the Roman past. The goal of the volume is to approach Visigothic customs not as an uncritical adoption and imitatio of contemporary Roman models (an "acculturation" model), but as unique interpretations of a common pool of symbols, practices, and institutions that formed the legacy of Rome. The contributors argue that it is necessary to reconsider the idea of imitatio imperii as a process that involved specific actors taking strategic decisions in historically contingent circumstances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, GermanicxRoman influences. 0aVisigothsxCultural assimilation. 0aVisigothsxSocial life and customs. 4aAntiquity. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aHistory. 4aMedieval Studies. 7aHISTORY / Byzantine Empire.2bisacsh  aVisigoths, Iberian Peninsula, medieval, late antiquity, Rome, Byzantium.1 aAddison, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrett, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchberger, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastellanos, Santiago, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristys, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenberg, Merle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández, Damián, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández, Damián, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHilsdale, Cecily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLester, Molly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLester, Molly, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.